{"title_page": "Fish Lake (Utah)", "text_new": "{{Infobox lake\n | name = \n | image = FishLake.JPG\n | caption = Bowery Resort in the foreground and the Mytoges to the left\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Sevier County, Utah|Sevier County]], [[Utah]],<br>[[United States]]\n | coords = {{coord|38|32|55|N|111|42|40|W |region:US-UT_type:waterbody |display=inline,title}} \n | type = \n | inflow =2535.35 \n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length = {{convert|5|mi|abbr=on}}\n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = {{convert|175|ft|abbr=on}}\n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = {{convert|8848|ft|abbr=on}}\n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Fish Lake''' is a high [[Alpine climate|alpine]] [[lake]] (elevation approximately {{convert|8848|ft|m|-1|abbr=on|disp=or}}) located in the Fishlake/ Southern Wasatch Plateau region of south-central [[Utah]], [[United States]]. It lies within and is the namesake of the [[Fishlake National Forest]].\n\nFish Lake is five miles long and 2 miles wide and one mile deep. It lies in a geologic structure known as a [[graben]] valley, formed by a underground once active volcano. It is bounded by the [[Mytoge Mountains]] on the southeast shore which sharply rise about 1,000&nbsp;feet (300&nbsp;m) above the lake level. Along the northwest shore, the lake is bounded by Fish Lake Hightop Plateau and the petersens from time to time. (summit elevation 11,600&nbsp;ft / 3,500&nbsp;m). The lake has an average depth of 85&nbsp;ft (26&nbsp;m).<ref>[http://www.fishlake.com fishlake.com] [https://documents.deq.utah.gov/water-quality/watershed-protection/DWQ-1997-001761.pdf#page=224 Fish Lake]</ref>\n\nFish Lake holds [[Rainbow Trout]], [[Splake]], [[Lake Trout]], [[Kokanee Salmon]], [[Brown Trout]], [[Tiger Trout]] and [[Yellow Perch]].  Yellow Perch are regarded as an invasive species; there is no bag limit and anglers are encouraged to dispose of any Yellow Perch caught.<ref>[http://wildlife.utah.gov/guidebooks/2015_pdfs/2015_fishing_low.pdf 2015 Utah Fishing Guidebook]</ref>  The lake is stocked by the [[Utah Division of Wildlife Resources]] [[fish hatchery]] in [[Glenwood, Utah|Glenwood]].  The region sees heavy snowfall in the winter, with snowfall occurring as late as June in any given year.  For this reason tourist activity is at its peak in the summer months.\n\n[[Pando (tree)|Pando]], a clonal quaking [[aspen]] stand, that, according to some sources, is the oldest (80,000 years) and largest (106 acres, 13 million pounds) organism on Earth, is located 1 mile southwest of Fish Lake on Utah route 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/fishlake/home/?cid=STELPRDB5393641|title=Pando|publisher=USDA Forest Service|accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest town is [[Koosharem, Utah|Koosharem]], 15&nbsp;miles to the west (24&nbsp;km).  A larger community, [[Richfield, Utah|Richfield]], is within a one-hour drive.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/fish_lake/yellow_perch.html A guide to yellow perch fishing at Fish Lake]\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/fish_lake/fish_lake_lake_trout.pdf |title=A Study of The Lake Trout Population At Fish Lake, Utah During 1989-2002 }}&nbsp;{{small|(761&nbsp;[[Kibibyte|KiB]])}} by the Utah Division of Wildlife Resources\n* {{cite web|url= https://documents.deq.utah.gov/water-quality/watershed-protection/DWQ-1997-001761.pdf#page=224 |title=Fish Lake }}&nbsp; by the [[Utah Department of Environmental Quality]]\n* [http://www.utahfishinginfo.com/utahlakes/fishlake.php Fish Lake fishing]\n* {{cite gnis|id=1441083|name=Fish Lake|accessdate=2009-05-04}}\n\n[[Category:Fishlake National Forest]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Utah]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Sevier County, Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n | name = \n | image = FishLake.JPG\n | caption = Bowery Resort in the foreground and the Mytoges to the left\n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Sevier County, Utah|Sevier County]], [[Utah]],<br>[[United States]]\n | coords = {{coord|38|32|55|N|111|42|40|W |region:US-UT_type:waterbody |display=inline,title}} \n | type = \n | inflow =2535.35 \n | outflow = \n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = United States\n | length = {{convert|5|mi|abbr=on}}\n | width = \n | area = \n | depth = \n | max-depth = {{convert|175|ft|abbr=on}}\n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = {{convert|8848|ft|abbr=on}}\n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Fish Lake''' is a high [[Alpine climate|alpine]] [[lake]] (elevation approximately {{convert|8848|ft|m|-1|abbr=on|disp=or}}) located in the Fishlake/ Southern Wasatch Plateau region of south-central [[Utah]], [[United States]]. It lies within and is the namesake of the [[Fishlake National Forest]].\n\nFish Lake is five miles long and 2 miles wide and one mile deep. It lies in a geologic structure known as a [[graben]] valley, formed by a underground once active volcano. It is bounded by the [[Mytoge Mountains]] on the southeast shore which sharply rise about 1,000&nbsp;feet (300&nbsp;m) above the lake level. Along the northwest shore, the lake is bounded by Fish Lake Hightop Plateau (summit elevation 11,600&nbsp;ft / 3,500&nbsp;m). The lake has an average depth of 85&nbsp;ft (26&nbsp;m) and has a maximum depth of 175 feet (53 m).<ref>[http://www.fishlake.com fishlake.com] [https://documents.deq.utah.gov/water-quality/watershed-protection/DWQ-1997-001761.pdf#page=224 Fish Lake]</ref>\n\nFish Lake holds [[Rainbow Trout]], [[Splake]], [[Lake Trout]], [[Kokanee Salmon]], [[Brown Trout]], [[Tiger Trout]] and [[Yellow Perch]].  Yellow Perch are regarded as an invasive species; there is no bag limit and anglers are encouraged to dispose of any Yellow Perch caught.<ref>[http://wildlife.utah.gov/guidebooks/2015_pdfs/2015_fishing_low.pdf 2015 Utah Fishing Guidebook]</ref>  The lake is stocked by the [[Utah Division of Wildlife Resources]] [[fish hatchery]] in [[Glenwood, Utah|Glenwood]].  The region sees heavy snowfall in the winter, with snowfall occurring as late as June in any given year.  For this reason tourist activity is at its peak in the summer months.\n\n[[Pando (tree)|Pando]], a clonal quaking [[aspen]] stand, that, according to some sources, is the oldest (80,000 years) and largest (106 acres, 13 million pounds) organism on Earth, is located 1 mile southwest of Fish Lake on Utah route 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/fishlake/home/?cid=STELPRDB5393641|title=Pando|publisher=USDA Forest Service|accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest town is [[Koosharem, Utah|Koosharem]], 15&nbsp;miles to the west (24&nbsp;km).  A larger community, [[Richfield, Utah|Richfield]], is within a one-hour drive.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/fish_lake/yellow_perch.html A guide to yellow perch fishing at Fish Lake]\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/fish_lake/fish_lake_lake_trout.pdf |title=A Study of The Lake Trout Population At Fish Lake, Utah During 1989-2002 }}&nbsp;{{small|(761&nbsp;[[Kibibyte|KiB]])}} by the Utah Division of Wildlife Resources\n* {{cite web|url= https://documents.deq.utah.gov/water-quality/watershed-protection/DWQ-1997-001761.pdf#page=224 |title=Fish Lake }}&nbsp; by the [[Utah Department of Environmental Quality]]\n* [http://www.utahfishinginfo.com/utahlakes/fishlake.php Fish Lake fishing]\n* {{cite gnis|id=1441083|name=Fish Lake|accessdate=2009-05-04}}\n\n[[Category:Fishlake National Forest]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Utah]]\n[[Category:Lakes of Sevier County, Utah]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1012:b146:815a:599b:cc76:5cd4:f86", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_Lake_(Utah)"}
