{"title_page": "Helperby", "text_new": "{{Short description|Village and former civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country =                  England      \n|official_name =            Helperby\n|coordinates   = {{coord|54.122200|-1.328400|display=inline,title}}\n| population = 520\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170216852|title=Helperby Parish |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n |civil_parish =             [[Brafferton and Helperby]]\n|shire_district =           [[Hambleton District|Hambleton]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|shire_county =             [[North Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton]]\n|post_town =                YORK\n|postcode_district =        YO61\n|postcode_area =            YO   \n|dial_code =             \n|os_grid_reference =        SE439698 \n|static_image             = Golden Lion, Helperby.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 240px\n|static_image_caption     = Golden Lion on Main Street\n}}\n\n'''Helperby''' is a village and former [[civil parish]], now in the parish of [[Brafferton and Helperby]], in the [[Hambleton District]] of [[North Yorkshire]], England, about five miles west of [[Easingwold]].<ref name=OS99>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 99 ''Northallerton & Ripon (Pateley Bridge & Leyburn)''|ISBN= 9780319231593 |publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2013}}</ref> Over the years it has joined onto [[Brafferton, North Yorkshire|Brafferton]]. On 1 April 2019 the parish was merged with Brafferton to form \"Brafferton and Helperby\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s3-eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/lgbce/Reviews/Yorkshire%20and%20the%20Humber/North%20Yorkshire/CGRs/Hambleton%20DC%20(ROCG)%20Brafferton%20%26%20Helperby%202019-02.pdf|title=The Hambleton District Council (Reorganisation of Community Governance) (Brafferton and Helperby) Order 2019|publisher=[[Local Government Boundary Commission for England]]|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHelperby has the Millennium Village Hall, a butcher's shop and a doctor's surgery.   There are two pubs, one a restaurant with rooms, one a village inn, and two churches, a [[Church of England]] and a disused [[Methodist]] Chapel which is now a house. In 2008 Helperby had a new pavilion at the football and cricket pitch.\n\nThere is also an annual beer festival held in September to raise funds for future development of a Children's play area.\n\n[[Image:Millennium Hall, Helperby, North Yorkshire.jpg|thumb|left|Helperby's Millennium Hall\n]]\nThe film ''[[The Life and Crimes of William Palmer]]'' was filmed in the village in 1998.\n\n==Governance==\nAn [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] in the same name exists. This ward had a total population of 1,922 at the Census 2011.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1237325067|title=Helperby 2011 Census Ward|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Helperby}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Hambleton District]]\n\n\n{{Hambleton-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Village and former civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country =                  England      \n|official_name =            Helperby\n|coordinates   = {{coord|54.122200|-1.328400|display=inline,title}}\n| population = 520\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170216852|title=Helperby Parish |accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n |civil_parish =             [[Brafferton and Helperby]]\n|shire_district =           [[Hambleton District|Hambleton]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|shire_county =             [[North Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton]]\n|post_town =                YORK\n|postcode_district =        YO61\n|postcode_area =            YO   \n|dial_code =             \n|os_grid_reference =        SE439698 \n|static_image             = Golden Lion, Helperby.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 240px\n|static_image_caption     = Golden Lion on Main Street\n}}\n\n'''Helperby''' is a village and former [[civil parish]], now in the parish of [[Brafferton and Helperby]], in the [[Hambleton District]] of [[North Yorkshire]], England, about five miles west of [[Easingwold]].<ref name=OS99>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 99 ''Northallerton & Ripon (Pateley Bridge & Leyburn)''|ISBN= 9780319231593 |publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2013}}</ref> Over the years it has joined onto [[Brafferton, North Yorkshire|Brafferton]]. On 1 April 2019 the parish was merged with Brafferton to form \"Brafferton and Helperby\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s3-eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/lgbce/Reviews/Yorkshire%20and%20the%20Humber/North%20Yorkshire/CGRs/Hambleton%20DC%20(ROCG)%20Brafferton%20%26%20Helperby%202019-02.pdf|title=The Hambleton District Council (Reorganisation of Community Governance) (Brafferton and Helperby) Order 2019|publisher=[[Local Government Boundary Commission for England]]|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHelperby has the Millennium Village Hall, a butcher's shop, a village store and cafe and a doctor's surgery.   There are two pubs, one a restaurant with rooms, one a village inn, and two churches, a [[Church of England]] and a disused [[Methodist]] Chapel which is now a house. In 2008 Helperby had a new pavilion at the football and cricket pitch.\n\nThere is also an annual beer festival held in September to raise funds for future development of a Children's play area.\n\n[[Image:Millennium Hall, Helperby, North Yorkshire.jpg|thumb|left|Helperby's Millennium Hall\n]]\nThe film ''[[The Life and Crimes of William Palmer]]'' was filmed in the village in 1998.\n\n==Governance==\nAn [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] in the same name exists. This ward had a total population of 1,922 at the Census 2011.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1237325067|title=Helperby 2011 Census Ward|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Helperby}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Hambleton District]]\n\n\n{{Hambleton-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "HelperbyQ", "label": "safe", "comment": "The shop and cafe closed down about three months ago.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helperby"}
{"title_page": "Ethnic groups in Kerala", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n[[File:Kathakali of kerala.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Kathakali]] is popular art form in Kerala'']]\n\nThe population of [[Kerala]], [[India]] is a heterogenous group that comprises many [[ethnic groups]] that originated in other parts of [[India]] as well as the world, with distinctive cultural and religious traditions. While the majority of Keralans speak the [[Malayalam language]], various ethnic groups may speak other languages as well.<ref name=\"\u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101than2006\">{{Cite book\n | last = \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101than | first =  E\u1e43\n | year = 2006\n | title = K\u0113ra\u1e37attile bh\u0101\u1e63aka\u1e37\n | isbn = 978-81-87590-11-8\n | publisher = Ant\u0101r\u0101\u1e63tr\u0332a K\u0113ra\u1e37apa\u1e6dhanak\u0113ndra\u1e43\n | location = Tiruvantapura\u1e43\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Ma\u1e47alil2006\">{{Cite book\n | last = Ma\u1e47alil | first =  P\u014d\u1e37\n | year = 2006\n | title = K\u0113ra\u1e37attile bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101ny\u016bnapak\u1e63a\u1e45\u1e45a\u1e37 : s\u0101m\u016bhika caritr\u0332a\u1e43\n | isbn = 978-81-8264-226-3\n | publisher = M\u0101tr\u0325bh\u016bmi Buks\n | location = Kolzhikode\n}}</ref>\n\nThe racial and ethnic history of Kerala is highly controversial and disputed among the cultural anthropologists, historians and other scholars. The people of Kerala, known as Malayali (people speaking [[Malayalam language]]), are polygenetic and belong to different ethnic groups and religions. The Census of India does not recognise [[Racial groups of India|racial]] or ethnic groups within India.<ref>Kumar, Jayant. Census of India. 2001. 4 September 2006. [http://www.censusindia.gov.in/ Indian Census]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5XlqpiwgC?url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/ |date=12 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>Dr. E, J. Thomas,\"The People of Kerala,\" The St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, Ed. George Menachery, Vol. II, 1973, p.185 et. sq.</ref> According to a 2009 study published by David Reich et al., the modern Indian population is composed of two genetically divergent and heterogeneous populations which mixed in ancient times, known as [[Ancestral North Indians]] (ANI, Indo-Aryan-speaking population) and [[Ancestral South Indians]] (ASI, Dravidian-speaking population).<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature08365 |title=Reconstructing Indian population history |year=2009 |last1=Reich |first1=David |last2=Thangaraj |first2=Kumarasamy |last3=Patterson |first3=Nick |last4=Price |first4=Alkes L. |last5=Singh |first5=Lalji |journal=Nature |volume=461 |issue=7263 |pages=489\u201394 |pmid=19779445 |pmc=2842210 |ref=harv|bibcode=2009Natur.461..489R }}</ref>\n\n*   Negrito element: the earliest racial strain in the population of Kerala as of [[South India]] in general. These people still live in forests of Kerala state. Most of these tribes' have curly hair, black skin, round head and broad nose.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\">Menon, A Sreedhara; \"A Survey of Kerala History\"; D C Books, 1 January 2007 \u2013 History \u2013 pp 54\u201356 [https://books.google.com/books?id=FVsw35oEBv4C&dq=A+Survey+Of+Kerala+History&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref>\n\n:e.g.: Hill tribes such as [[Kadar (tribe)|Kadar]], [[Kanikkaran|Kanikkar]], Malapandarams, Mutuvans, Ullatans, Uralis, Paniyas etc.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\" />\n\n*   Proto-Australoids: the Negritos were probably replaced by Proto-Australoids. These people have flat nose and dark skin.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\" />\n\n==Malayali==\n\n{{Main|Malayali}}\nMalayalis are the native people of Kerala who speak Malayalam, the official language of the state. The [[Malayalam language]] is a [[Dravidian language]] possibly related to [[Tamil Language|Tamil]] which crystallised into a distinctive tongue only at the beginning of the medieval era. Similar to other major languages, modern Malayalam includes [[loanwords]] from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Syriac language|Syriac]], and in more recent times English.<ref name=George1972>{{Cite book\n | last = George | first =  K.M | year = 1972 | title = Western influence on Malayalam language and literature | isbn = 978-81-260-0413-3 | publisher = Sahitya Akademi | location = New Delhi}}</ref> While the majority of Malayalis live in Kerala, significant populations also exist in other parts of [[India]], the Middle East, Europe and North America. According to the Indian census of 1991, there were 28,096,376 speakers of Malayalam in Kerala, making up 96.66% of the total population of that state.\n\nThe majority (about 54%) of the Malayali people are [[Hindu]], mostly of the [[Ezhava]], [[Ambalavasi]], [[Namboothiri]], [[Nair]], [[Kammalar]] ([[Vishwakarma]]), [[Pulayan]] and [[Kerala Mukkuvar|Mukkuvar]] communities, but there are also large [[Muslim]] (24%) and [[Christians|Christian]] (18%) communities.<ref name=2001census>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Census_Data_Online/Language/Statement3.htm Linguistic minorities of Kerala]</ref> The Islam religion, reached Malabar Coast, of which the Kerala state is a part of, as early as the 7th century AD through [[Arab]] traders and mostly follow the [[Shafi`i]] school of [[Sunni Islam]]. Many speak the distinctive [[Mappila dialect of Malayalam]].<ref>[http://www.deepthi.com/kerala/about-kerala/kerala-history.html ''Kerala History''] Deepthi.com. Retrieved 10 March 2009\n.</ref> There is also a sizable population of [[Rowther]]s, who have a Turkish ancestry. The majority of Christians belong to the [[Saint Thomas Christian]] community, and are also known as ''Syrian Christians'' or ''Nasrani''.<ref name=\"Grantz\">Gantz Brothers, Land of the Perumals 1863</ref> The Nasranis/Syrian Christians have presence in Kerala as far as from 1st century AD. [[Thomas the Apostle|St. Thomas]] the Apostle-one of the twelve disciples of the [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]] came to [[Muziris]] on the Kerala coast in AD 52. The descendants of the [[Cochin Jews]] who have traditionally followed [[Halakha|Halakhic Judaism]] are known as ''Juda Mappila''<ref name=\"BMalieckal\">Bindu Malieckal (2005);</ref> have settled in Kerala before the Christian era of which many endorsed Christianity from 1st century AD and remaining Jews have finally started returning to Israel from 1948. In that vast period of their settlement they have explicitly marked their presence in Kerala like the [[Paradesi Synagogue|Paradeshi Synagogue]] at Kochi and many of returnees from Kerala in Israel still speaks a dialect of Malayalam called [[Judeo-Malayalam]].\n\n==Tamil==\n{{See also|Kerala Iyers}}\n\nHistorically, there have been frequent migrations between Kerala and the neighbouring state of [[Tamil Nadu]]. The history of ancient Kerala itself is deeply intertwined with Tamil Nadu's ancient past, and the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] languages are closely related. The dialect of Tamil spoken today in the district of [[Palakkad]] in Kerala has a large number of Malayalam loanwords, has been influenced by Malayalam syntax and also has a distinct Malayalam accent.<ref>Thiru. Mu. Kovint\u0101c\u0101riyar, ''{{IAST|V\u0101\u1e3baiya\u1e6di v\u0101\u1e3bai}}'' Lifco, Madras, 1978 at pp. 26\u201339.</ref>\n\nSome of the earliest migrations attested by history were those of [[Iyers]] from the [[Cauvery delta]] to the district of Palakkad. The first of these migrations are believed to have taken place over five hundred years ago. These Iyers settled in Palakkad where they owned land and led an affluent existence till the enactment of the land reforms in the 1960s. They followed many Malayali practices include the practice of ''[[sambandham]]''. There have also been migrations of Iyers to the princely state of [[Travancore]] from the [[Tirunelveli district]] during the 18th and 19th centuries. These Iyers are called [[Kerala Iyers]] and differ significantly from [[Palakkad Iyers]] in their language and social status. Some of Travancore's ''[[diwans]]'' were Tamil Brahmins.<ref name=\"Kerala\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kuzhalmannamagraharam.info/articles/kerala-iyer-history.html|title=History of Kerala iyers and Agraharams|accessdate=2008-08-27|publisher=Kuzhalmanna Agraharam website|author=}}</ref><ref name=\"keralaiyers_migration\">{{cite web|url=http://www.keralaiyers.com/migration|title=Migration Theories|accessdate=2008-08-19|publisher=keralaiyers.com}}</ref>\n\nApart from Iyers, many other Tamil communities also migrated to Kerala between the 18th and the 20th century when the southernmost [[Kanyakumari district]] of Tamil Nadu was a part of the [[Travancore]] kingdom. The capital of the Travancore kingdom which ruled over most of Kerala was located in [[Padmanabhapuram]] in present-day Tamil Nadu. The caste system in Kerala is very similar to that which exists in the southern districts of Tamil Nadu.<ref>[http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf ''Towards Modern Kerala, 10th Standard Text Book, Chapter 9.''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217193847/http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf |date=17 December 2008 }} www.education.kerala.gov.in</ref>\n\nKerala is also the home to a sizable population of [[Sri Lankan Tamils]] who arrived as refugees as a result of the [[Sri Lankan civil war]], as well as [[Indian Tamils of Sri Lanka]] who were displaced due to the [[Ceylon Citizenship Act]]. The latter number close to 10,000 and are mainly found in eastern parts of the [[Kollam district]] where they work in rubber plantations under the [[Government of Kerala]]'s initiative Rehabilitation Plantations Limited.<ref name=\"cc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.countercurrents.org/shaji230607.htm | title=Rubber Boom Raises Hope Of Repatriates | publisher=Counter Currents | accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> \n\nThe Tamil caste of [[Vellalar]]s migrated from Tamil Nadu to eastern parts of Kerala like Idukki and Pathanamthitta districts. They are prominently found in places including Erattupetta, Pala, Ponkunnam, Kanjirappalli, Thodupuzha, and Pathanamthitta. Similarly, Tamil Muslims migrated the same route from Madurai to the regions of Thodupuzha, Irattupetta, and Pathanamthitta. They are distinct from Malayalam speaking Mappila Muslims in many ways including the usage of a dialect of Tamil inside their houses.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Tulu==\n\n{{main|Shivalli Tulu Brahmins of Kerala}}\nShivalli Brahmins living all over the Indian state of [[Kerala]] are part of the larger Tulu Brahmin subsect primarily found in the Indian state of [[Karnataka]] but also in the [[Kasaragod district]] and [[Kannur]] of Northern Kerala. Their mother tongue is the [[Tulu language]].  Brahmins from Tulunadu may have migrated to Kerala before the first century&nbsp;C.E.<ref>[http://www.madhwabrahmanasabha.org/history.htm ''Kerala History''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224816/http://madhwabrahmanasabha.org/history.htm |date=22 January 2009 }} Udupi Madhwa Brahmana Sabha (Kerala).  Retrieved 9 March 2009.</ref> Today, there is a sizeable Tulu Brahmin population in [[Thiruvananthapuram]] and elsewhere in the state.<ref>[http://www.kakkilaya.com/shiva1.html ''The History of Shivalli Brahmins''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924213804/http://www.kakkilaya.com/shiva1.html |date=24 September 2006 }} Kakkilayas of Bevinje. Retrieved 9 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==Kannada==\n\n{{Main|Kannada people}}\n\nKannada is one of the major languages of [[India]], spoken predominantly in the state of [[Karnataka]]. The [[Kannada people]] number roughly 50 million, making it the fifteenth-most spoken language in the world.<ref name=\"encarta_lang_10million\">''[http://encarta.msn.com/media_701500404/Languages_Spoken_by_More_Than_10_Million_People.html Languages Spoken by More Than 10 Million People]''. [[Encarta]]. {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5kwPyXpQ1?url=http://encarta.msn.com/media_701500404/Languages_Spoken_by_More_Than_10_Million_People.html |date=31 October 2009 }} 2009-10-31.</ref> It is one of the [[official languages of India]] and the official and administrative language of the state of Karnataka.<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://dpal.kar.nic.in/26%20of%201963%20(E).pdf|format=PDF|title=The Karnataka Official Language Act|work=Official website of Department of Parliamentary Affairs and Legislation|publisher=Government of Karnataka|accessdate=2007-06-29}}</ref> Kannada people constitute a significant portion of the population of the district of [[Kasargod district|Kasargod]] in North Kerala. [[Kannada]] is also an administrative language in the district.\n\n==Konkanis==\nCochin GSB's are a branch of the [[Konkani language]]-speaking [[Gaud Saraswat Brahmins]] community belonging originally to Karnataka and Goa. They form the majority of Konkani-speakers in Kerala. GSBs of Cochin form the southernmost subsect of [[Saraswat Brahmins]] of West coast. GSBs of north Kerala are same as GSBs of [[Kanara|Canara]] in speech and customs, whereas GSBs of Cochin and Travancore have developed their own [[Konkani language|Konkani]] dialect and Customs, which distinguish them from rest of GSB community, this subsect is now called Cochin GSBs. In geographical terms, Cochin GSBs are those who live south of Thrissur district of Kerala.<ref name=Kudva1972>{{Cite book | last = Kudva | first =  Venkataraya Narayan | year = 1972 | title = History of the Dakshinatya Saraswats | publisher = Samyukta Gowda Saraswata Sabha}}</ref> Other Konkani speaking minorities in Kerala include the [[Kudumbi]]s, [[Daivajna]]s, and the [[Vaishya Vani]]. All these groups had migrated from Goa within last few centuries for various socioeconomic reasons.\n\n{{see also|Cochin GSB's}}\n\n==Mahls==\n\nThere are about 10,000 speakers of the [[Mahl language]] in Kerala. Most Mahl speakers are temporary resident people from neighbouring [[Maldives]]. Other Mahl speakers are from Indian island of [[Minicoy]] and most of them live in [[Trivandrum]].\n\n==Smaller minority groups==\n\n===Gujaratis===\nThere are about 500 [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] families living for many generations in [[Kochi, India|Kochi]], the commercial hub of [[Kerala]]. Gujarati community is composed of various social groups like [[Jainism|Jains]], [[Saurashtra people|Saurashtrians]] and [[Kutchi people|Kutchis]]. The Gujarati Street at Mattancherry in the city is a main Gujarati cultural icon in Kerala.<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2002/10/07/stories/2002100700380200.htm ''It's Dandiya time again''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323152659/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2002/10/07/stories/2002100700380200.htm |date=23 March 2008 }} The Hindu.  Retrieved 9 March 2009</ref> [[Kozhikode|Calicut]], [[Thrissur]], and [[Cannanore]] also have a sizeable population of Hindu and [[Jainism|Jain]] Gujaratis.<ref>[http://www.jaintemplecochin.org/advent.htm The Advent of Gujrathi's in Kerala]</ref> {{Citation needed span|text=They are basically business people doing all forms of wholesale and retail trade.|date=January 2019|reason=}} There is a Gujarati Higher Secondary School near Calicut Beach.<ref>{{cite news|publisher = The Hindu|title = Students eager to master life skills |url = http://www.hindu.com/2006/10/19/stories/2006101900170200.htm|date = \n19 October 2006|accessdate = 10 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Sikhs===\n\n{{main|Cochin Sikhs}}\n[[Kochi, India|Kochi]] is home to the [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] speaking [[Sikh]] community in Kerala as the coastal city has the most number of Sikhs in the south Indian state.  Many of the Kerala's Punjabi Sikh community are in the automobile spare parts industry.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Other minorities===\nKerala also have a small number of scattered Bengali, Bihari and Oriya communities.\n\n==List of mother tongues spoken in Kerala by number of speakers==\n[[File:Cochin Jews.jpg|thumb|200px|An Indian Jewish family in [[Cochin]], circa 1900.]]\n[[File:Onapottan - A Traditional Kerala Art Form.jpg|thumb|right|200px|`Onapottan' \u2013 a folk character seen during Onam season specially in North Malabar Region. With the face painted and crown ( Kireedam ) he has a bell in his hand and an umbrella made of Palm Leaves on the other.]]\n[[File:AntonyIndia.jpg|thumb|200px|[[A.K. Antony]] former [[Defence Minister of India]] is an [[atheist]] who was born to a Malayali family in the [[Alappuzha]] district of Kerala]]\n(Excluding the tribal population)<ref>Keralathile Bhashakal (Languages of Kerala) By Dr. M. Sreenadhan. Published by International Centre for Kerala Studies, University of Kerala, Kariavattom, Thiruvananthapuram.</ref>{{when|date=May 2015}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Language\n! No. of speakers\n! % of population\n|-\n| [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| 28,096,376\n| 96.66\n|-\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| 616,010\n| 2.12\n|-\n| [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n| {{formatnum:325571}} \n| 1.2\n|-\n| [[Tulu language|Tulu]]\n| 111,670\n| 0.38\n|-\n| [[Konkani language|Konkani]]\n| 64,008\n| 0.22\n|-\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| 47,216\n| 0.16\n|-\n| [[Hindi]]\n| 21,751\n| 0.07\n|-\n| [[Urdu]]\n| 12,625\n| 0.04\n|-\n| [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n| 6,369\n| 0.02\n|-\n| English\n| 3,002\n| 0.01\n|-\n| [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| 2,201\n| 0.008\n|-\n| [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| 1,919\n| 0.007\n|-\n| [[Nepali language|Nepali]]\n| 1,312\n| 0.005\n|-\n| [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]\n| 1,185\n| 0.004\n|-\n| [[Oriya language|Oriya]]\n| 733\n| 0.003\n|-\n| [[Dilli language|Dilli]]\n| 277\n| 0.001\n|-\n| [[Assamese language|Assamese]]\n| 264\n| 0.001\n|-\n| [[Arabic]]\n| 243\n| 0.001\n|-\n| Other languages\n|  4256\n|  0.15\n|-\n| Total\n| 29,067,481\n| 100%\n|}\n\n==Religion and Community==\n[[File:Pongale1.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Hindu women worship during [[Attukal Temple|Attukal Pongala]] at Tippu Street, South Fort, Thiruvananthapuram.]]\n[[File:Malik dinar mosque.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Malik Dinar Mosque]], Thazhathangadi, [[Kasaragod district|Kasargode]], Kerala.]]\n[[File:Kottayam Valia Palli02.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Inside a Knanaya Church in Thazhathangadi, Kottayam]]\nAccording to the 2001 census<ref name=2001census/> the breakdown of ethnic groups by religion is:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  || Malayalam || Other languages || Total\n|-\n| '''Hindu''' || 54.20% || 2% || '''56.20%'''\n|-\n| '''Muslim''' || 23.70% || 1% || '''24.70%'''\n|-\n| '''Christian''' || 18.00% || 1% || '''19.00%'''\n|-\n| '''Other religions''' || <0.1% || <0.1% || '''00.10%'''\n|-\n| '''Total''' || '''96.00%''' || '''4.00%''' || '''100.00%'''\n|}\n\n==1968 Socio-Economic Survey of Kerala==\nIn 1968, the Communist government under [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]] ordered a socio-economic survey of each resident in the state of Kerala, to assess caste inequalities. Until the census of 2011, this survey was the only caste-based count conducted in post-independence India.{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} The survey was not very conclusive, since it merged several unrelated castes into one group (for example, Ambalavasis and Tamil Brahmins were grouped along with Malayali Brahmins).{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nThe survey found that individuals belonging to higher castes possessed more land and had relatively higher per capita income as compared to the general population.{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} The survey found that 33% of the states population was [[forward caste]], almost half of whom were [[Saint Thomas Christians|Syrian Christians]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} According to the survey, 13% of the Brahmins, 6.8% of the [[Syro-Malabar|Syrian Catholics]], 5.4% of the [[Malankara Orthodox Church |Jacobites]] and 4.7% of the Nairs owned more than 5 acres of land. This compared with 1.4% of the Ezhavas, 1.9% of the Muslims and 0.1% of the Scheduled Castes who had that much land in their possession.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 4367366|title = Caste, Class and Economic Opportunity in Kerala: An Empirical Analysis|journal = Economic and Political Weekly|volume = 14|issue = 7/8|pages = 475\u2013480|last1 = Sivanandan|first1 = P|year = 1979}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population of Kerala, per the 1968 Socio-Economic Survey{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n!Caste\n!Population\n!Percentage\n|-\n|Brahmin\n|353,329\n|1.76%\n|-\n|Nair\n|2,905,775\n|14.46%\n|-\n|Nair Other\n|435,396\n|2.17%\n|-\n|Kammalar\n|756,178\n|3.76%\n|-\n|Vellalar / Chetty\n|151,150\n|0.75%\n|-\n|Kaniyan/ Izhava/ Nadar/ Ezhava\n|4,457,808\n|22.19%\n|-\n|Arayan / Mukkuvan\n|851,603\n|4.24%\n|-\n|Scheduled Castes\n|1,578,115\n|7.85%\n|-\n|Ezhuthachan \n|260,042\n|1.29%\n|-\n|Syrian & Latin Rite Catholics\n|3,214,278\n|16.00%\n|-\n|Orthodox & Marthomite \n|731,207\n|3.64%\n|-\n|Christian Scheduled Caste\n|301,912\n|1.50%\n|-\n|Muslim\n|3,842,322\n|19.12%\n|-\n|Scheduled Tribe\n|253,519\n|1.26%\n|-\n|Total\n|20,092,634\n|100.00%\n|}\n\nThe last comprehensive caste census of Kerala was undertaken by the British in 1931 (the Census of 1941 also asked caste, but the tables were never published).<ref>Census 1931 of Travancore (Imper. Table XVII), Census 1931 of Cochin (Imper Table VXII) & Census 1931 of Madras Vol.2, p.306-310</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!'''Caste'''\n!'''Population (1931)'''\n!'''Percentage (1931)'''\n|-\n|Malayali Brahmin\n|50,240\n|0.51%\n|-\n|Foreign Brahmin\n|121,748\n|1.24%\n|-\n|Ambalavasi Brahmin\n|39,371\n|0.40%\n|-\n|Samanta Kshatriya\n|5,901\n|0.06%\n|-\n|Samanthan Nair\n|4,921\n|0.05%\n|-\n|Nair \n|1,505,929\n|15.30%\n|-\n|Vilakkithala Nair\n|35,199\n|0.36%\n|-\n|Veluthedath Nair\n|22,219\n|0.23%\n|-\n|Kammalar\n|265,752\n|2.70%\n|-\n|Vellalar\n|88,584\n|0.90%\n|-\n|Chetty\n|49,213\n|0.50%\n|-\n|Izhava + Thiyya\n|2,007,901\n|20.40%\n|-\n|Kaniyar\n|39,371\n|0.40%\n|-\n|Mukkuvar + Arayar\n|88,584\n|0.90%\n|-\n|Parayar\n|165,656\n|1.68%\n|-\n|Pulayar + Cherumar\n|678,387\n|6.89%\n|-\n|Kuravan\n|95,295\n|0.97%\n|-\n|Thandan\n|41,214\n|0.42%\n|-\n|Nadar\n|402,555\n|4.09%\n|-\n|Christians\n|2,005,239\n|18.37%\n|-\n|Muslim\n|1,604,629\n|16.30%\n|-\n|Total\n|9,842,650\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Religion in Kerala]]\n* [[Caste system in Kerala]]\n* [[Migrant labourers in Kerala]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethnic Groups In Kerala}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Kerala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n[[File:Kathakali of kerala.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Kathakali]] is popular art form in Kerala'']]\n\nThe population of [[Kerala]], [[India]] is a heterogenous group that comprises many [[ethnic groups]] that originated in other parts of [[India]] as well as the world, with distinctive cultural and religious traditions. While the majority of Keralans speak the [[Malayalam language]], various ethnic groups may speak other languages as well.<ref name=\"\u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101than2006\">{{Cite book\n | last = \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101than | first =  E\u1e43\n | year = 2006\n | title = K\u0113ra\u1e37attile bh\u0101\u1e63aka\u1e37\n | isbn = 978-81-87590-11-8\n | publisher = Ant\u0101r\u0101\u1e63tr\u0332a K\u0113ra\u1e37apa\u1e6dhanak\u0113ndra\u1e43\n | location = Tiruvantapura\u1e43\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Ma\u1e47alil2006\">{{Cite book\n | last = Ma\u1e47alil | first =  P\u014d\u1e37\n | year = 2006\n | title = K\u0113ra\u1e37attile bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101ny\u016bnapak\u1e63a\u1e45\u1e45a\u1e37 : s\u0101m\u016bhika caritr\u0332a\u1e43\n | isbn = 978-81-8264-226-3\n | publisher = M\u0101tr\u0325bh\u016bmi Buks\n | location = Kolzhikode\n}}</ref>\n\nThe racial and ethnic history of Kerala is highly controversial and disputed among the cultural anthropologists, historians and other scholars. The people of Kerala, known as Malayali (people speaking [[Malayalam language]]), are polygenetic and belong to different ethnic groups and religions. The Census of India does not recognise [[Racial groups of India|racial]] or ethnic groups within India.<ref>Kumar, Jayant. Census of India. 2001. 4 September 2006. [http://www.censusindia.gov.in/ Indian Census]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5XlqpiwgC?url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/ |date=12 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>Dr. E, J. Thomas,\"The People of Kerala,\" The St. Thomas Christian Encyclopaedia of India, Ed. George Menachery, Vol. II, 1973, p.185 et. sq.</ref> According to a 2009 study published by David Reich et al., the modern Indian population is composed of two genetically divergent and heterogeneous populations which mixed in ancient times, known as [[Ancestral North Indians]] (ANI, Indo-Aryan-speaking population) and [[Ancestral South Indians]] (ASI, Dravidian-speaking population).<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature08365 |title=Reconstructing Indian population history |year=2009 |last1=Reich |first1=David |last2=Thangaraj |first2=Kumarasamy |last3=Patterson |first3=Nick |last4=Price |first4=Alkes L. |last5=Singh |first5=Lalji |journal=Nature |volume=461 |issue=7263 |pages=489\u201394 |pmid=19779445 |pmc=2842210 |ref=harv|bibcode=2009Natur.461..489R }}</ref>\n\n*   Negrito element: the earliest racial strain in the population of Kerala as of [[South India]] in general. These people still live in forests of Kerala state. Most of these tribes' have curly hair, black skin, round head and broad nose.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\">Menon, A Sreedhara; \"A Survey of Kerala History\"; D C Books, 1 January 2007 \u2013 History \u2013 pp 54\u201356 [https://books.google.com/books?id=FVsw35oEBv4C&dq=A+Survey+Of+Kerala+History&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref>\n\n:e.g.: Hill tribes such as [[Kadar (tribe)|Kadar]], [[Kanikkaran|Kanikkar]], Malapandarams, Mutuvans, Ullatans, Uralis, Paniyas etc.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\" />\n\n*   Proto-Australoids: the Negritos were probably replaced by Proto-Australoids. These people have flat nose and dark skin.<ref name=\"A Survey Of Kerala History\" />\n\n==Malayali==\n\n{{Main|Malayali}}\nMalayalis are the native people of Kerala who speak Malayalam, the official language of the state. The [[Malayalam language]] is a [[Dravidian language]] possibly related to [[Tamil Language|Tamil]] which crystallised into a distinctive tongue only at the beginning of the medieval era. Similar to other major languages, modern Malayalam includes [[loanwords]] from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Syriac language|Syriac]], and in more recent times English.<ref name=George1972>{{Cite book\n | last = George | first =  K.M | year = 1972 | title = Western influence on Malayalam language and literature | isbn = 978-81-260-0413-3 | publisher = Sahitya Akademi | location = New Delhi}}</ref> While the majority of Malayalis live in Kerala, significant populations also exist in other parts of [[India]], the Middle East, Europe and North America. According to the Indian census of 1991, there were 28,096,376 speakers of Malayalam in Kerala, making up 96.66% of the total population of that state.\n\nThe majority (about 54%) of the Malayali people are [[Hindu]], mostly of the [[Ezhava]], [[Ambalavasi]], [[Namboothiri]], [[Nair]], [[Kammalar]] ([[Vishwakarma]]), [[Pulayan]] and [[Kerala Mukkuvar|Mukkuvar]] communities, but there are also large [[Muslim]] (24%) and [[Christians|Christian]] (18%) communities.<ref name=2001census>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Census_Data_Online/Language/Statement3.htm Linguistic minorities of Kerala]</ref> The Muslim community, or [[Mappila]]s, trace their origins far back to early contacts with [[Arab]] traders before the start of the [[Anno Domini|Christian era]], and mostly follow the [[Shafi`i]] school of [[Sunni Islam]]. Many speak the distinctive [[Mappila dialect of Malayalam]].<ref>[http://www.deepthi.com/kerala/about-kerala/kerala-history.html ''Kerala History''] Deepthi.com. Retrieved 10 March 2009\n.</ref> There is also a sizable population of [[Rowther]]s, who have a Turkish ancestry. The majority of Christians belong to the [[Saint Thomas Christian]] community, and are also known as ''Syrian Christians'' or ''Nasrani''.<ref name=\"Grantz\">Gantz Brothers, Land of the Perumals 1863</ref> The descendants of the [[Cochin Jews]] who have traditionally followed [[Halakha|Halakhic Judaism]] are known as ''Juda Mappila''.<ref name=\"BMalieckal\">Bindu Malieckal (2005);</ref>\n\n==Tamil==\n{{See also|Kerala Iyers}}\n\nHistorically, there have been frequent migrations between Kerala and the neighbouring state of [[Tamil Nadu]]. The history of ancient Kerala itself is deeply intertwined with Tamil Nadu's ancient past, and the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] languages are closely related. The dialect of Tamil spoken today in the district of [[Palakkad]] in Kerala has a large number of Malayalam loanwords, has been influenced by Malayalam syntax and also has a distinct Malayalam accent.<ref>Thiru. Mu. Kovint\u0101c\u0101riyar, ''{{IAST|V\u0101\u1e3baiya\u1e6di v\u0101\u1e3bai}}'' Lifco, Madras, 1978 at pp. 26\u201339.</ref>\n\nSome of the earliest migrations attested by history were those of [[Iyers]] from the [[Cauvery delta]] to the district of Palakkad. The first of these migrations are believed to have taken place over five hundred years ago. These Iyers settled in Palakkad where they owned land and led an affluent existence till the enactment of the land reforms in the 1960s. They followed many Malayali practices include the practice of ''[[sambandham]]''. There have also been migrations of Iyers to the princely state of [[Travancore]] from the [[Tirunelveli district]] during the 18th and 19th centuries. These Iyers are called [[Kerala Iyers]] and differ significantly from [[Palakkad Iyers]] in their language and social status. Some of Travancore's ''[[diwans]]'' were Tamil Brahmins.<ref name=\"Kerala\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kuzhalmannamagraharam.info/articles/kerala-iyer-history.html|title=History of Kerala iyers and Agraharams|accessdate=2008-08-27|publisher=Kuzhalmanna Agraharam website|author=}}</ref><ref name=\"keralaiyers_migration\">{{cite web|url=http://www.keralaiyers.com/migration|title=Migration Theories|accessdate=2008-08-19|publisher=keralaiyers.com}}</ref>\n\nApart from Iyers, many other Tamil communities also migrated to Kerala between the 18th and the 20th century when the southernmost [[Kanyakumari district]] of Tamil Nadu was a part of the [[Travancore]] kingdom. The capital of the Travancore kingdom which ruled over most of Kerala was located in [[Padmanabhapuram]] in present-day Tamil Nadu. The caste system in Kerala is very similar to that which exists in the southern districts of Tamil Nadu.<ref>[http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf ''Towards Modern Kerala, 10th Standard Text Book, Chapter 9.''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217193847/http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf |date=17 December 2008 }} www.education.kerala.gov.in</ref>\n\nKerala is also the home to a sizable population of [[Sri Lankan Tamils]] who arrived as refugees as a result of the [[Sri Lankan civil war]], as well as [[Indian Tamils of Sri Lanka]] who were displaced due to the [[Ceylon Citizenship Act]]. The latter number close to 10,000 and are mainly found in eastern parts of the [[Kollam district]] where they work in rubber plantations under the [[Government of Kerala]]'s initiative Rehabilitation Plantations Limited.<ref name=\"cc\">{{cite web | url=http://www.countercurrents.org/shaji230607.htm | title=Rubber Boom Raises Hope Of Repatriates | publisher=Counter Currents | accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> \n\nThe Tamil caste of [[Vellalar]]s migrated from Tamil Nadu to eastern parts of Kerala like Idukki and Pathanamthitta districts. They are prominently found in places including Erattupetta, Pala, Ponkunnam, Kanjirappalli, Thodupuzha, and Pathanamthitta. Similarly, Tamil Muslims migrated the same route from Madurai to the regions of Thodupuzha, Irattupetta, and Pathanamthitta. They are distinct from Malayalam speaking Mappila Muslims in many ways including the usage of a dialect of Tamil inside their houses.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Tulu==\n\n{{main|Shivalli Tulu Brahmins of Kerala}}\nShivalli Brahmins living all over the Indian state of [[Kerala]] are part of the larger Tulu Brahmin subsect primarily found in the Indian state of [[Karnataka]] but also in the [[Kasaragod district]] and [[Kannur]] of Northern Kerala. Their mother tongue is the [[Tulu language]].  Brahmins from Tulunadu may have migrated to Kerala before the first century&nbsp;C.E.<ref>[http://www.madhwabrahmanasabha.org/history.htm ''Kerala History''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122224816/http://madhwabrahmanasabha.org/history.htm |date=22 January 2009 }} Udupi Madhwa Brahmana Sabha (Kerala).  Retrieved 9 March 2009.</ref> Today, there is a sizeable Tulu Brahmin population in [[Thiruvananthapuram]] and elsewhere in the state.<ref>[http://www.kakkilaya.com/shiva1.html ''The History of Shivalli Brahmins''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924213804/http://www.kakkilaya.com/shiva1.html |date=24 September 2006 }} Kakkilayas of Bevinje. Retrieved 9 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==Kannada==\n\n{{Main|Kannada people}}\n\nKannada is one of the major languages of [[India]], spoken predominantly in the state of [[Karnataka]]. The [[Kannada people]] number roughly 50 million, making it the fifteenth-most spoken language in the world.<ref name=\"encarta_lang_10million\">''[http://encarta.msn.com/media_701500404/Languages_Spoken_by_More_Than_10_Million_People.html Languages Spoken by More Than 10 Million People]''. [[Encarta]]. {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5kwPyXpQ1?url=http://encarta.msn.com/media_701500404/Languages_Spoken_by_More_Than_10_Million_People.html |date=31 October 2009 }} 2009-10-31.</ref> It is one of the [[official languages of India]] and the official and administrative language of the state of Karnataka.<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://dpal.kar.nic.in/26%20of%201963%20(E).pdf|format=PDF|title=The Karnataka Official Language Act|work=Official website of Department of Parliamentary Affairs and Legislation|publisher=Government of Karnataka|accessdate=2007-06-29}}</ref> Kannada people constitute a significant portion of the population of the district of [[Kasargod district|Kasargod]] in North Kerala. [[Kannada]] is also an administrative language in the district.\n\n==Konkanis==\nCochin GSB's are a branch of the [[Konkani language]]-speaking [[Gaud Saraswat Brahmins]] community belonging originally to Karnataka and Goa. They form the majority of Konkani-speakers in Kerala. GSBs of Cochin form the southernmost subsect of [[Saraswat Brahmins]] of West coast. GSBs of north Kerala are same as GSBs of [[Kanara|Canara]] in speech and customs, whereas GSBs of Cochin and Travancore have developed their own [[Konkani language|Konkani]] dialect and Customs, which distinguish them from rest of GSB community, this subsect is now called Cochin GSBs. In geographical terms, Cochin GSBs are those who live south of Thrissur district of Kerala.<ref name=Kudva1972>{{Cite book | last = Kudva | first =  Venkataraya Narayan | year = 1972 | title = History of the Dakshinatya Saraswats | publisher = Samyukta Gowda Saraswata Sabha}}</ref> Other Konkani speaking minorities in Kerala include the [[Kudumbi]]s, [[Daivajna]]s, and the [[Vaishya Vani]]. All these groups had migrated from Goa within last few centuries for various socioeconomic reasons.\n\n{{see also|Cochin GSB's}}\n\n==Mahls==\n\nThere are about 10,000 speakers of the [[Mahl language]] in Kerala. Most Mahl speakers are temporary resident people from neighbouring [[Maldives]]. Other Mahl speakers are from Indian island of [[Minicoy]] and most of them live in [[Trivandrum]].\n\n==Smaller minority groups==\n\n===Gujaratis===\nThere are about 500 [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] families living for many generations in [[Kochi, India|Kochi]], the commercial hub of [[Kerala]]. Gujarati community is composed of various social groups like [[Jainism|Jains]], [[Saurashtra people|Saurashtrians]] and [[Kutchi people|Kutchis]]. The Gujarati Street at Mattancherry in the city is a main Gujarati cultural icon in Kerala.<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2002/10/07/stories/2002100700380200.htm ''It's Dandiya time again''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323152659/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2002/10/07/stories/2002100700380200.htm |date=23 March 2008 }} The Hindu.  Retrieved 9 March 2009</ref> [[Kozhikode|Calicut]], [[Thrissur]], and [[Cannanore]] also have a sizeable population of Hindu and [[Jainism|Jain]] Gujaratis.<ref>[http://www.jaintemplecochin.org/advent.htm The Advent of Gujrathi's in Kerala]</ref> {{Citation needed span|text=They are basically business people doing all forms of wholesale and retail trade.|date=January 2019|reason=}} There is a Gujarati Higher Secondary School near Calicut Beach.<ref>{{cite news|publisher = The Hindu|title = Students eager to master life skills |url = http://www.hindu.com/2006/10/19/stories/2006101900170200.htm|date = \n19 October 2006|accessdate = 10 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Sikhs===\n\n{{main|Cochin Sikhs}}\n[[Kochi, India|Kochi]] is home to the [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] speaking [[Sikh]] community in Kerala as the coastal city has the most number of Sikhs in the south Indian state.  Many of the Kerala's Punjabi Sikh community are in the automobile spare parts industry.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Other minorities===\nKerala also have a small number of scattered Bengali, Bihari and Oriya communities.\n\n==List of mother tongues spoken in Kerala by number of speakers==\n[[File:Cochin Jews.jpg|thumb|200px|An Indian Jewish family in [[Cochin]], circa 1900.]]\n[[File:Onapottan - A Traditional Kerala Art Form.jpg|thumb|right|200px|`Onapottan' \u2013 a folk character seen during Onam season specially in North Malabar Region. With the face painted and crown ( Kireedam ) he has a bell in his hand and an umbrella made of Palm Leaves on the other.]]\n[[File:AntonyIndia.jpg|thumb|200px|[[A.K. Antony]] former [[Defence Minister of India]] is an [[atheist]] who was born to a Malayali family in the [[Alappuzha]] district of Kerala]]\n(Excluding the tribal population)<ref>Keralathile Bhashakal (Languages of Kerala) By Dr. M. Sreenadhan. Published by International Centre for Kerala Studies, University of Kerala, Kariavattom, Thiruvananthapuram.</ref>{{when|date=May 2015}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Language\n! No. of speakers\n! % of population\n|-\n| [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| 28,096,376\n| 96.66\n|-\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| 616,010\n| 2.12\n|-\n| [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n| {{formatnum:325571}} \n| 1.2\n|-\n| [[Tulu language|Tulu]]\n| 111,670\n| 0.38\n|-\n| [[Konkani language|Konkani]]\n| 64,008\n| 0.22\n|-\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| 47,216\n| 0.16\n|-\n| [[Hindi]]\n| 21,751\n| 0.07\n|-\n| [[Urdu]]\n| 12,625\n| 0.04\n|-\n| [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n| 6,369\n| 0.02\n|-\n| English\n| 3,002\n| 0.01\n|-\n| [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| 2,201\n| 0.008\n|-\n| [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| 1,919\n| 0.007\n|-\n| [[Nepali language|Nepali]]\n| 1,312\n| 0.005\n|-\n| [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]\n| 1,185\n| 0.004\n|-\n| [[Oriya language|Oriya]]\n| 733\n| 0.003\n|-\n| [[Dilli language|Dilli]]\n| 277\n| 0.001\n|-\n| [[Assamese language|Assamese]]\n| 264\n| 0.001\n|-\n| [[Arabic]]\n| 243\n| 0.001\n|-\n| Other languages\n|  4256\n|  0.15\n|-\n| Total\n| 29,067,481\n| 100%\n|}\n\n==Religion and Community==\n[[File:Pongale1.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Hindu women worship during [[Attukal Temple|Attukal Pongala]] at Tippu Street, South Fort, Thiruvananthapuram.]]\n[[File:Malik dinar mosque.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Malik Dinar Mosque]], Thazhathangadi, [[Kasaragod district|Kasargode]], Kerala.]]\n[[File:Kottayam Valia Palli02.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Inside a Knanaya Church in Thazhathangadi, Kottayam]]\nAccording to the 2001 census<ref name=2001census/> the breakdown of ethnic groups by religion is:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  || Malayalam || Other languages || Total\n|-\n| '''Hindu''' || 54.20% || 2% || '''56.20%'''\n|-\n| '''Muslim''' || 23.70% || 1% || '''24.70%'''\n|-\n| '''Christian''' || 18.00% || 1% || '''19.00%'''\n|-\n| '''Other religions''' || <0.1% || <0.1% || '''00.10%'''\n|-\n| '''Total''' || '''96.00%''' || '''4.00%''' || '''100.00%'''\n|}\n\n==1968 Socio-Economic Survey of Kerala==\nIn 1968, the Communist government under [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]] ordered a socio-economic survey of each resident in the state of Kerala, to assess caste inequalities. Until the census of 2011, this survey was the only caste-based count conducted in post-independence India.{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} The survey was not very conclusive, since it merged several unrelated castes into one group (for example, Ambalavasis and Tamil Brahmins were grouped along with Malayali Brahmins).{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nThe survey found that individuals belonging to higher castes possessed more land and had relatively higher per capita income as compared to the general population.{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} The survey found that 33% of the states population was [[forward caste]], almost half of whom were [[Saint Thomas Christians|Syrian Christians]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} According to the survey, 13% of the Brahmins, 6.8% of the [[Syro-Malabar|Syrian Catholics]], 5.4% of the [[Malankara Orthodox Church |Jacobites]] and 4.7% of the Nairs owned more than 5 acres of land. This compared with 1.4% of the Ezhavas, 1.9% of the Muslims and 0.1% of the Scheduled Castes who had that much land in their possession.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 4367366|title = Caste, Class and Economic Opportunity in Kerala: An Empirical Analysis|journal = Economic and Political Weekly|volume = 14|issue = 7/8|pages = 475\u2013480|last1 = Sivanandan|first1 = P|year = 1979}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population of Kerala, per the 1968 Socio-Economic Survey{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n!Caste\n!Population\n!Percentage\n|-\n|Brahmin\n|353,329\n|1.76%\n|-\n|Nair\n|2,905,775\n|14.46%\n|-\n|Nair Other\n|435,396\n|2.17%\n|-\n|Kammalar\n|756,178\n|3.76%\n|-\n|Vellalar / Chetty\n|151,150\n|0.75%\n|-\n|Kaniyan/ Izhava/ Nadar/ Ezhava\n|4,457,808\n|22.19%\n|-\n|Arayan / Mukkuvan\n|851,603\n|4.24%\n|-\n|Scheduled Castes\n|1,578,115\n|7.85%\n|-\n|Ezhuthachan \n|260,042\n|1.29%\n|-\n|Syrian & Latin Rite Catholics\n|3,214,278\n|16.00%\n|-\n|Orthodox & Marthomite \n|731,207\n|3.64%\n|-\n|Christian Scheduled Caste\n|301,912\n|1.50%\n|-\n|Muslim\n|3,842,322\n|19.12%\n|-\n|Scheduled Tribe\n|253,519\n|1.26%\n|-\n|Total\n|20,092,634\n|100.00%\n|}\n\nThe last comprehensive caste census of Kerala was undertaken by the British in 1931 (the Census of 1941 also asked caste, but the tables were never published).<ref>Census 1931 of Travancore (Imper. Table XVII), Census 1931 of Cochin (Imper Table VXII) & Census 1931 of Madras Vol.2, p.306-310</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!'''Caste'''\n!'''Population (1931)'''\n!'''Percentage (1931)'''\n|-\n|Malayali Brahmin\n|50,240\n|0.51%\n|-\n|Foreign Brahmin\n|121,748\n|1.24%\n|-\n|Ambalavasi Brahmin\n|39,371\n|0.40%\n|-\n|Samanta Kshatriya\n|5,901\n|0.06%\n|-\n|Samanthan Nair\n|4,921\n|0.05%\n|-\n|Nair \n|1,505,929\n|15.30%\n|-\n|Vilakkithala Nair\n|35,199\n|0.36%\n|-\n|Veluthedath Nair\n|22,219\n|0.23%\n|-\n|Kammalar\n|265,752\n|2.70%\n|-\n|Vellalar\n|88,584\n|0.90%\n|-\n|Chetty\n|49,213\n|0.50%\n|-\n|Izhava + Thiyya\n|2,007,901\n|20.40%\n|-\n|Kaniyar\n|39,371\n|0.40%\n|-\n|Mukkuvar + Arayar\n|88,584\n|0.90%\n|-\n|Parayar\n|165,656\n|1.68%\n|-\n|Pulayar + Cherumar\n|678,387\n|6.89%\n|-\n|Kuravan\n|95,295\n|0.97%\n|-\n|Thandan\n|41,214\n|0.42%\n|-\n|Nadar\n|402,555\n|4.09%\n|-\n|Christians\n|2,005,239\n|18.37%\n|-\n|Muslim\n|1,604,629\n|16.30%\n|-\n|Total\n|9,842,650\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Religion in Kerala]]\n* [[Caste system in Kerala]]\n* [[Migrant labourers in Kerala]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethnic Groups In Kerala}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "\u0d15\u0d7c\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d23\u0d7b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethnic_groups_in_Kerala"}
{"title_page": "Cluster B personality disorders", "text_new": "{{Personality disorders sidebar}}'''Cluster B personality disorders''' are a categorization of [[personality disorders]] as defined in the [[DSM-IV]] and [[DSM-5]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.verywell.com/the-cluster-b-personality-disorders-425429|title=Understanding the Cluster B Personality Disorders/The Cluster B Personality Disorders: What Are the Cluster B Personality Disorders?|author=Kristalyn Salters-Pedneault|date=May 6, 2016|work=Verywell|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906103716/http://bpd.about.com/od/relatedconditions/a/clusterB.htm|archivedate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThese disorders are characterized by dramatic, overly emotional or unpredictable thinking or behavior and  interactions with others. They include antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, histrionic personality disorder and narcissistic personality disorder.<ref name=\"mayoclinic.org2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/personality-disorders/symptoms-causes/syc-20354463|title=Personality disorders - Symptoms and causes|website=Mayo Clinic|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe British National Health Service has described those with this disorder as someone who, \"struggles to relate to others. As a result, they show patterns of behaviour most would regard as dramatic, erratic and threatening or disturbing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/personality-disorder/|title=Personality disorder|date=26 October 2017|website=nhs.uk|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Four Recognized Cluster B Personality Disorders:<ref name=\"mayoclinic.org2\" /> ==\nEach of these disorders, while similar, have a variety of symptoms, diagnoses, and causes.\n\n* [https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/000921.htm Antisocial personality disorder]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/000921.htm|title=Antisocial personality disorder: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|website=medlineplus.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> ([[DSM-IV Codes|DSM-IV code]] 301.7):   '''Symptoms:''' Indifferent and routine manipulation, exploitation, and violation of the rights of others. It can also be characterized by routine [[Crime|law breaking]].<ref name=\":0\" />    '''Cause:''' Signs of Antisocial Personality disorder often first become evident in childhood. Consequently, although the cause is unknown, it is believed that a more difficult childhood can lead to APD.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/antisocial-personality-disorder/|title=Antisocial personality disorder|date=2018-03-21|website=nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>    '''Diagnosis:''' While symptoms can start to show themselves in the early teen years, a diagnosis cannot be made until adulthood. To be diagnosed, the patient must fit at least three of the most common indicators such as recklessness, irresponsibility, apathy, and irritability.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* [https://www.nami.org/learn-more/mental-health-conditions/borderline-personality-disorder#targetText=Borderline%20Personality%20Disorder%20(BPD)%20is,after%20an%20emotionally%20triggering%20event. Borderline personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.83):   '''Symptoms:''' Difficulty regulating emotions,  impulsivity, self harm, dissociative feelings, and even psychotic episodes.     '''Cause:'''   1. Genetics - Those with a family member who has BPD are considered more likely to develop the disorder.  2. Trauma - Trauma such as assault or neglect early in life may lead to BPD.    '''Diagnosis:''' Unlike many psychological disorders, there is no strict guideline for the diagnosis of Borderline Personality Disorder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nami.org/learn-more/mental-health-conditions/borderline-personality-disorder|title=Borderline Personality Disorder|last=|first=|date=December 2017|website=National Alliance on Mental Illness|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n* [https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/9743-histrionic-personality-disorder Histrionic personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.50):   '''Symptoms:''' an overwhelming desire for attention, chronically unstable emotions, sensitivity, gullibility, and reckless behavior.    '''Cause:''' It is believed that Histrionic Personality Disorder can either be inherited genetically or learned behavior in early childhood.    '''Diagnosis:''' To diagnose the disorder, there is no strict guideline; however, a doctor may begin by evaluating the patient's medical history and physical well-being to ensure that the causes of the symptoms are mental rather than physical.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/9743-histrionic-personality-disorder|title=Histrionic Personality Disorder|website=Cleveland Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n* [https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/narcissistic-personality-disorder/symptoms-causes/syc-20366662#targetText=Narcissistic%20personality%20disorder%20%E2%80%94%20one%20of,lack%20of%20empathy%20for%20others. Narcissistic personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.81):   '''Symptoms:'''  a magnified sense of self importance, underlying deep self esteem issues, exaggeration, manipulation, envy, arrogance, impatience, depression. Like [[Histrionic personality disorder|HPD]], it can cause an excessive need for attention and approval.     '''Causes:''' It can be caused by genetics, environment, or neurobiology.    '''Diagnosis:''' NPD may often go misdiagnosed or undiagnosed, as patients often display symptoms similar to other disorders, or may not be willing to admit there is anything wrong. It may be treated with talk therapy (psychotherapy).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/narcissistic-personality-disorder/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20366690|title=Narcissistic personality disorder - Diagnosis and treatment - Mayo Clinic|website=www.mayoclinic.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Cluster B traits and common symptoms ==\nCluster B personality disorders are all characterized by emotional dysregulation, impulsivity, and frequent interpersonal conflicts. These individuals present as \"dramatic\", \"emotional\", and \"erratic\".<ref name=\"DSM5\">{{cite book |title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders |date=2013 |publisher=American Psychiatric Association |page=646 |edition=5th |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6818303/ |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The predominant theme and shared trait among Cluster B personalities is a lack of emotional empathy.<ref name=\"K&R\">{{cite journal |last1=Kraus |first1=G |last2=Reynolds |first2=DJ |title=The \"A-B-C's\" of the cluster B's: identifying, understanding, and treating cluster B personality disorders |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |date=April 2001 |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=345-373 |doi=10.1016/s0272-7358(99)00052-5 |pmid=11288605 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6818303/#cit0022 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Dr. Simon Baron-Cohen posited that empathy is a spectrum, at one end of the distribution lies the \"zero-negative empathy\", this is where antisocial, borderline, and narcissistic personality disorders are placed, which is why individuals with these personality disorders are capable of dehumanizing others, leading to acts of cruelty. Borderlines, sociopaths, and narcissists are considered \"zero-negative empathy\" because they are \"unequivocally bad for the sufferers and all those around them\". Dr. Baron-Cohen did not include histrionic personality disorder in the zero negative empathy category because they are capable of empathy. Individuals with histrionic personality disorder have a greater capacity for dependent relations than do those with narcissistic, borderline, and antisocial personality disorders, and they are more emotionally expressive and less dismissive of others.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Caligor |first1=E. |last2=Levy |first2=KN |last3=Yeomans |first3=FE |title=Narcissistic Personality Disorder: Diagnostic and Clinical Challenges |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=5 May 2015 |volume=172 |issue=5 |pages=415-422 |url=https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/10.1176/appi.ajp.2014.14060723 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last1=Baron-Cohen |first1=Simon |title=Zero Degrees of Empathy: A New Theory of Human Cruelty |date=2011 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=London, UK |isbn=9780713997910 |pages=190 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275290115_Zero_Degrees_of_Empathy_A_New_Theory_of_Human_Cruelty |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Causes and Risk Factors ==\nPersonality disorders are likely caused by a combination of genetics and environmental factors. In a study, information found a strong correlation between borderline personality disorder and history of sexual trauma. Research has found a significant link between cluster B personality disorders and family history as well. Having a parent or sibling with a personality disorder increases your risk for developing the disorder. Furthermore, this research proves that family history plays a huge role in one parent, sibling, or relative obtaining the disorder.\n\n== Treatment and Medications ==\nTreatment centers around the use of psychotherapy. There are no medications approved by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] for the treatment of personality disorders. However, medications are sometimes prescribed to target symptom domains (e.g. aggression and explosive anger, impulsivity) or treat co-occurring mental health problems.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[DSM-5#Personality disorders|Personality disorders in the DSM-5]]\n* [[Histrionic personality disorder]]\n* [[Narcissistic personality disorder]]\n* [[Borderline personality disorder]]\n* [[Antisocial personality disorder]] \n*[[Treatment of mental disorders]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Personality disorders| Cluster B]]\n", "text_old": "{{Personality disorders sidebar}}'''Cluster B personality disorders''' are a categorization of [[personality disorders]] as defined in the [[DSM-IV]] and [[DSM-5]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.verywell.com/the-cluster-b-personality-disorders-425429|title=Understanding the Cluster B Personality Disorders/The Cluster B Personality Disorders: What Are the Cluster B Personality Disorders?|author=Kristalyn Salters-Pedneault|date=May 6, 2016|work=Verywell|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906103716/http://bpd.about.com/od/relatedconditions/a/clusterB.htm|archivedate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThese disorders are characterized by dramatic, overly emotional or unpredictable thinking or behavior and  interactions with others. They include antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, histrionic personality disorder and narcissistic personality disorder.<ref name=\"mayoclinic.org2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/personality-disorders/symptoms-causes/syc-20354463|title=Personality disorders - Symptoms and causes|website=Mayo Clinic|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe British National Health Service has described those with this disorder as someone who, \"struggles to relate to others. As a result, they show patterns of behaviour most would regard as dramatic, erratic and threatening or disturbing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/personality-disorder/|title=Personality disorder|date=26 October 2017|website=nhs.uk|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Four Recognized Cluster B Personality Disorders:<ref name=\"mayoclinic.org2\" /> ==\nEach of these disorders, while similar, have a variety of symptoms, diagnoses, and causes.\n\n* [https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/000921.htm Antisocial personality disorder]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/000921.htm|title=Antisocial personality disorder: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|website=medlineplus.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> ([[DSM-IV Codes|DSM-IV code]] 301.7):   '''Symptoms:''' Indifferent and routine manipulation, exploitation, and violation of the rights of others. It can also be characterized by routine [[Crime|law breaking]].<ref name=\":0\" />    '''Cause:''' Signs of Antisocial Personality disorder often first become evident in childhood. Consequently, although the cause is unknown, it is believed that a more difficult childhood can lead to APD.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/antisocial-personality-disorder/|title=Antisocial personality disorder|date=2018-03-21|website=nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>    '''Diagnosis:''' While symptoms can start to show themselves in the early teen years, a diagnosis cannot be made until adulthood. To be diagnosed, the patient must fit at least three of the most common indicators such as recklessness, irresponsibility, apathy, and irritability.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* [https://www.nami.org/learn-more/mental-health-conditions/borderline-personality-disorder#targetText=Borderline%20Personality%20Disorder%20(BPD)%20is,after%20an%20emotionally%20triggering%20event. Borderline personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.83):   '''Symptoms:''' Difficulty regulating emotions,  impulsivity, self harm, dissociative feelings, and even psychotic episodes.     '''Cause:'''   1. Genetics - Those with a family member who has BPD are considered more likely to develop the disorder.  2. Trauma - Trauma such as assault or neglect early in life may lead to BPD.    '''Diagnosis:''' Unlike many psychological disorders, there is no strict guideline for the diagnosis of Borderline Personality Disorder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nami.org/learn-more/mental-health-conditions/borderline-personality-disorder|title=Borderline Personality Disorder|last=|first=|date=December 2017|website=National Alliance on Mental Illness|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n* [https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/9743-histrionic-personality-disorder Histrionic personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.50):   '''Symptoms:''' an overwhelming desire for attention, chronically unstable emotions, sensitivity, gullibility, and reckless behavior.    '''Cause:''' It is believed that Histrionic Personality Disorder can either be inherited genetically or learned behavior in early childhood.    '''Diagnosis:''' To diagnose the disorder, there is no strict guideline, however a doctor may begin by evaluating the patient's medical history and physical well-being to ensure that the causes of the symptoms are mental rather than physical.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/9743-histrionic-personality-disorder|title=Histrionic Personality Disorder|website=Cleveland Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \n* [https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/narcissistic-personality-disorder/symptoms-causes/syc-20366662#targetText=Narcissistic%20personality%20disorder%20%E2%80%94%20one%20of,lack%20of%20empathy%20for%20others. Narcissistic personality disorder] (DSM-IV code 301.81):   '''Symptoms:'''  a magnified sense of self importance, underlying deep self esteem issues, exaggeration, manipulation, envy, arrogance, impatience, depression. Like [[Histrionic personality disorder|HPD]], it can cause an excessive need for attention and approval.     '''Causes:''' It can be caused by genetics, environment, or neurobiology.    '''Diagnosis:''' NPD may often go misdiagnosed or undiagnosed, as patients often display symptoms similar to other disorders, or may not be willing to admit there is anything wrong. It may be treated with talk therapy (psychotherapy).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/narcissistic-personality-disorder/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20366690|title=Narcissistic personality disorder - Diagnosis and treatment - Mayo Clinic|website=www.mayoclinic.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Cluster B traits and common symptoms ==\nCluster B personality disorders are all characterized by emotional dysregulation, impulsivity, and frequent interpersonal conflicts. These individuals present as \"dramatic\", \"emotional\", and \"erratic\".<ref name=\"DSM5\">{{cite book |title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders |date=2013 |publisher=American Psychiatric Association |page=646 |edition=5th |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6818303/ |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The predominant theme and shared trait among Cluster B personalities is a lack of emotional empathy.<ref name=\"K&R\">{{cite journal |last1=Kraus |first1=G |last2=Reynolds |first2=DJ |title=The \"A-B-C's\" of the cluster B's: identifying, understanding, and treating cluster B personality disorders |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |date=April 2001 |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=345-373 |doi=10.1016/s0272-7358(99)00052-5 |pmid=11288605 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6818303/#cit0022 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Dr. Simon Baron-Cohen posited that empathy is a spectrum, at one end of the distribution lies the \"zero-negative empathy\", this is where antisocial, borderline, and narcissistic personality disorders are placed, which is why individuals with these personality disorders are capable of dehumanizing others, leading to acts of cruelty. Borderlines, sociopaths, and narcissists are considered \"zero-negative empathy\" because they are \"unequivocally bad for the sufferers and all those around them\". Dr. Baron-Cohen did not include histrionic personality disorder in the zero negative empathy category because they are capable of empathy. Individuals with histrionic personality disorder have a greater capacity for dependent relations than do those with narcissistic, borderline, and antisocial personality disorders, and they are more emotionally expressive and less dismissive of others.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Caligor |first1=E. |last2=Levy |first2=KN |last3=Yeomans |first3=FE |title=Narcissistic Personality Disorder: Diagnostic and Clinical Challenges |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=5 May 2015 |volume=172 |issue=5 |pages=415-422 |url=https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/10.1176/appi.ajp.2014.14060723 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last1=Baron-Cohen |first1=Simon |title=Zero Degrees of Empathy: A New Theory of Human Cruelty |date=2011 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=London, UK |isbn=9780713997910 |pages=190 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275290115_Zero_Degrees_of_Empathy_A_New_Theory_of_Human_Cruelty |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Causes and Risk Factors ==\nPersonality disorders are likely caused by a combination of genetics and environmental factors. In a study, information found a strong correlation between borderline personality disorder and history of sexual trauma. Research has found a significant link between cluster B personality disorders and family history as well. Having a parent or sibling with a personality disorder increases your risk for developing the disorder. Furthermore, this research proves that family history plays a huge role in one parent, sibling, or relative obtaining the disorder.\n\n== Treatment and Medications ==\nTreatment centers around the use of psychotherapy. There are no medications approved by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] for the treatment of personality disorders. However, medications are sometimes prescribed to target symptom domains (e.g. aggression and explosive anger, impulsivity) or treat co-occurring mental health problems.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[DSM-5#Personality disorders|Personality disorders in the DSM-5]]\n* [[Histrionic personality disorder]]\n* [[Narcissistic personality disorder]]\n* [[Borderline personality disorder]]\n* [[Antisocial personality disorder]] \n*[[Treatment of mental disorders]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Personality disorders| Cluster B]]\n", "name_user": "Zgystardst", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFour Recognized Cluster B Personality Disorders::fixed typos.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_B_personality_disorders"}
{"title_page": "Sarfaraz Khan (cricketer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = selvakumar\n| image = \n| fullname = Sarfaraz Khan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1998|12|26}}\n| birth_place = [[tamilnadu]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| nickname = \n| heightft = 5.10\n| heightinch =\n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[meedium fast]]\n| role = Batsman\n| country = India\n| club1 = [[team|Mumbai]]\n| year1 = 2013/14\u20132014/15\n| clubnumber1 = \n| club2 = [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]]\n| year2 = 2015\u20132018\n| clubnumber2 = 97\n| club3 = [[Uttar Pradesh cricket team|Uttar Pradesh]]\n| year3 = 2015/16\u20132017/18\n| clubnumber3 = \n| club4 = [[Kings XI Punjab]]\n| year4 = 2019\n| club5 = Mumbai\n| year5 = 2019/20\n| clubnumber5 = \n| columns = 3\n| column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| column2 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 cricket|T20]]\n| matches1 = 17\n| runs1 = 1,463\n| bat avg1 = 66.50\n| 100s/50s1 = 4/4\n| top score1 = 301[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries1 = 78\n| wickets1 = 0\n| bowl avg1 = \u2013\n| fivefor1 = \u2013\n| tenfor1 = \u2013\n| best bowling1 = \u2013\n| catches/stumpings1 = 11/\u2013\n| matches2 = 13\n| runs2 = 257\n| bat avg2 = 36.71\n| 100s/50s2 = 1/0\n| top score2 = 100\n| deliveries2 = 6\n| wickets2 = 0\n| bowl avg2 = \u2013\n| fivefor2 = \u2013\n| tenfor2 = \u2013\n| best bowling2 = \u2013\n| catches/stumpings2 = 6/\u2013\n| matches3 = 56\n| runs3 = 633\n| bat avg3 = 23.44\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/2\n| top score3 = 67\n| deliveries3 = 2\n| wickets3 = 0\n| bowl avg3 = \u2013\n| fivefor3 = \u2013\n| tenfor3 = \u2013\n| best bowling3 = \u2013\n| catches/stumpings3 = 19/\u2013\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/642525.html ESPN Cricinfo\n| date = 4 April\n| year = 2020\n}}\nSarfaraz Naushad Khan (born 27 October 1997) is an Indian [[cricket]]er who plays for Mumbai in the [[Ranji Trophy]] and for Kings XI Punjab in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/player/642525.html|title=Sarfaraz Khan|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> Nicknamed Panda for his love of food, Sarfaraz represented India in the [[Under-19 Cricket World Cup|ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup]] in 2014 and 2016. He is an aggressive right handed [[batsman]] and a part-time [[Spin bowling|spinner]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/in-en/sarfaraz-khan-stardom-at-17|title=Sarfaraz Khan- Stardom at 17|website=Red Bull|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nHe is the youngest player to play an IPL match and is the only uncapped<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/uncapped|title=Uncapped definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> player to be retained by a franchise in the IPL.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/9429/sarfaraz-khan|title=Sarfaraz Khan Profile \u2013 ICC Ranking, Age, Career Info & Stats|website=Cricbuzz|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/sports/cricket/article/ipl-player-retention-2018-twitter-stunned-by-rcb-decision-to-retain-sarfaraz-khan/185399|title=IPL Player Retention 2018: Twitter stunned by RCB's decision to retain Sarfaraz Khan|website=timesnownews.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> As a 15-year old in 2012, he was mentionined in to the prestigious [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] along with his younger brother Musheer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.mid-day.com/sports/2012/may/170512-sports-Sarfaraz-and-Musheer-Khan-ecstatic-to-make-Wisden.htm|title=Sarfaraz and Musheer Khan ecstatic to make Wisden|website=archive.mid-day.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and background ==\nSarfaraz was born and brought up in the suburbs of [[Mumbai]]. He spent most of his childhood in [[Azad Maidan]]. There Naushad Khan, his father and coach, nurtured young cricketers such as [[Iqbal Abdulla]] and [[Kamran Khan (Indian cricketer)|Kamran Khan]]. His coaching began at an early age when his father discovered his talent of timing the ball well. In monsoon conditions it was difficult for him to reach the ''maidan'' (grounds) from his home in the suburbs, so a synthetic pitch was laid besides his house for practice. \"Not only does it save our time and energy but it has also helped him get used to bouncier wickets that he will have to deal with later on,\" his father commented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-under-19-world-cup-2014/content/story/718683.html|title=Representing India and his father|date=14 February 2014|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was unable to attend school for 4 years due to his cricket commitments, so a private tutor was employed for his maths and English classes.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Youth and domestic career==\nHe came into the limelight when he broke the 45-year-old record of [[Sachin Tendulkar]] by scoring 439 off 421 balls in a Harris Shield game. It was his maiden Harris Shield game in 2009 when he was just 12 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/new-zealand-in-india-2016/top-stories/Wonder-boy-Sarfaraz-wants-to-meet-Sachin-Tendulkar/articleshow/5202527.cms|title=Wonder boy Sarfaraz wants to meet Sachin Tendulkar|website=The Times of India|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> He was playing for his school, Rizvi Springfield. The innings included 56 fours and 12 sixes.<ref name=\":0\" /> He soon started playing for the Mumbai Under-19 team and his performance for them led to selection for the [[India national under-19 cricket team|Indian Under-19 team]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2013, he scored a match-winning 66 ball 101 against [[South Africa national under-19 cricket team|South Africa Under 19s]], which included 17 fours and a six. [[Bharat Arun]], the then head coach of the India Under 19 team, commented that: \"He is a gusty player, who reads the situation well. He has shots all around the wicket and looks even better when playing straight. He uses his feet well and plays cheeky strokes too.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/new-zealand-in-india-2016/top-stories/Sarfaraz-Khan-15-slams-ton-against-South-Africa-U-19/articleshow/23066008.cms|title=Sarfaraz Khan, 15, slams ton against South Africa U-19|website=The Times of India|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSarfaraz played for India in two [[Under-19 Cricket World Cup|Under-19 World Cups]] (2014 and 2016). The [[2014 Under-19 Cricket World Cup|2014 Under-19 World Cup]] was played by 16 teams in a round robin format where India finished at the 5th position. He scored 211 runs in six games at an average of 70.33; two innings were fifties, and he ended up a strike rate of 105.5. Following this performance, IPL franchise [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] bought him for 5&nbsp;million for the 2015 season. India finished as runners up in the [[2016 Under-19 Cricket World Cup|2016 Under 19 World Cup]] in Bangladesh. In the tournament Sarfaraz finished as the second highest run scorer. He scored 355 runs from six innings, with five scores of over 50, at an average of 71.<ref name=\":0\" /> At the Under-19 level he has the record for most number of fifties in World Cups (7 fifties across two World Cups).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/sarfaraz-khan-creates-history-at-icc-under-19-world-cup-1487092|title=Sarfaraz Khan Creates History at ICC Under-19 World Cup {{!}} Cricket News|last=NDTVSports.com|website=NDTVSports.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSarfaraz started his [[Ranji Trophy|Ranji]] career with Mumbai when he played against Bengal in 2014. He started playing for Uttar Pradesh from the 2015\u20132016 season. By September 2019  he had played 11 first-class matches and has scored 535 runs with the highest score of 155. He had also played 12 list A matches and had scored 257 runs at a strike rate of 96.25.<ref name=\":0\" /> In January 2020, in the [[2019\u201320 Ranji Trophy]] match against [[Uttar Pradesh cricket team|Uttar Pradesh]], Sarfaraz scored his maiden [[List of Ranji Trophy triple centuries|triple century]] in first-class cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/sarfaraz-khan-mumbai-triple-hundred-ranji-trophy-uttar-pradesh-elite-list-gavaskar-rohit-sharma-1639152-2020-01-22 |title=Ranji Trophy: Sarfaraz Khan joins Rohit Sharma, Sanjay Manjrekar in elite list after 301 not out |work=India Today |accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies==\nIn 2011, a school team accused him of being overage. Bone tests showed him to have an age of 15 but according to the birth date registered with the [[Mumbai Cricket Association]] he was 13 years old. Sarfaraz and his father went for a second, advanced test. This time the resulting age matched with the registered birth date. Sarfaraz himself was disturbed by this controversy and it effected his emotional health. It took him two to three months to get his focus back on cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/tracing-sarfaraz-khans-controversial-cricketing-career/218524|title=Tracing Sarfaraz Khan's controversial cricketing career|date=18 June 2013|website=mid-day|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sarfaraz made some offensive gestures to the selectors after leading Mumbai to a victory in the Under-19 championship semi-final. As a consequence, he was dropped from the team and along with [[Suryakumar Yadav]] his match fees for two years were withhold as an assurance for his good behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/868521.html|title=Sarfaraz and Suryakumar's withheld Ranji fees|date=30 April 2015|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== IPL career==\nAfter a good performance in the 2014 Under-19 World Cup, Sarfaraz was bought by Royal Challengers Bangalore (RCB) in 2015 for 5&nbsp;million. At an age of 17, he is the youngest player to have ever participated in an IPL match.<ref name=\":2\" />  In his debut game against [[Chennai Super Kings]], he scored 11 runs off 7 balls. With the trio of [[Virat Kohli]], [[Chris Gayle]] and [[AB de Villiers]] dominating in the next two matches he did not get a chance to bat. In the next match he outshone the trio of more established batsmen, scoring 45 runs off 21 balls against [[Rajasthan Royals]]. The innings included six fours and a six and helped RCB post a large total. Virat Kohli bowed down to him while he was walking back to the dressing room at the end of the innings.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Citation|title=Sarfaraz Khan reacts on Virat Kohli bowing gesture|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ToTvbanJYB8|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> In total in the IPL season for 2015, he played 13 matches and scored 111 runs at a strike rate of 156.33.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iplt20.com/teams/royal-challengers-bangalore/squad/1564/sarfaraz-khan|title=IPLT20.com \u2013 Indian Premier League Official Website|website=iplt20.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> He started the 2016 season quickly when he played a cameo of 35 runs off 10 balls against [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]. In the 19th over he attacked the bowling of [[Bhuvneshwar Kumar|Bhuvaneshwar Kumar]], the best bowler of the tournament<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iplt20.com/stats/2016/most-wickets|title=IPLT20.com \u2013 Indian Premier League Official Website|website=iplt20.com|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> and scored 4 fours and a six. His teammate Chris Gayle commented that \"He's too young and he's like a son to me. He's definitely one for the future and one must keep an eye on him.\"  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-full-commentary/16392/rcb-vs-srh-4th-match-indian-premier-league-2016|title=Catch the Full Commentary of Royal Challengers Bangalore vs Sunrisers Hyderabad, 4th Match, Indian Premier League, 2016|website=Cricbuzz|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalchallengers.com/blog/sarfaraz-son-me-says-chris-gayle-9686|title=\"Sarfaraz is like a son to me\" says Chris Gayle|last=piyush|date=13 April 2016|website=Royal Challengers Bangalore|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe kept on having short, eventful innings in the 2016 season for RCB. Eventually he was dropped from the team due to his lack of fitness. In 2016 he ended up played 5 matches and scored 66 runs at a strike rate of 212.90.<ref name=\":3\" /> In the 2017 season he injured his leg during a training session and had to miss the entire season.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn a surprising move, RCB retained Sarfaraz over the likes of Chris Gayle, [[K. L. Rahul|K L Rahul]] and [[Yuzvendra Chahal]] for the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/sarfaraz-the-biggest-surprise-in-ipl-retentions/articleshow/62375674.cms|title=Sarfaraz, the biggest surprise in IPL retentions|website=The Times of India|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> Sarfaraz had a poor season and managed to score only 51 runs from six innings at a strike rate of 124.39.<ref name=\":3\" /> He was eventually released by RCB ahead of the 2019 season. [[Kings XI Punjab]] picked him up for the next season for just 2.5&nbsp;million. Having his former RCB team-mates like K L Rahul, Chris Gayle and [[Mandeep Singh]] helped him through this transfer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26369195/sarfaraz-khan-ready-fresh-reboot-kings-xi-punjab|title=Sarfaraz Khan \u2013 ready for a fresh reboot with Kings XI Punjab|date=27 March 2019|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref> He scored 180 runs from eight matches at an average of 45 and a highest score of 67 runs.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{cricinfo|id=642525}}\n\n{{Kings XI Punjab squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Sarfaraz}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Mumbai cricketers]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh cricketers]]\n[[Category:Royal Challengers Bangalore cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Sarfaraz Khan\n| image = \n| fullname = Sarfaraz Khan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1997|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| nickname = Panda\n| heightft = \n| heightinch =\n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[off break]]\n| role = Batsman\n| country = India\n| club1 = [[Mumbai cricket team|Mumbai]]\n| year1 = 2013/14\u20132014/15\n| clubnumber1 = \n| club2 = [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]]\n| year2 = 2015\u20132018\n| clubnumber2 = 97\n| club3 = [[Uttar Pradesh cricket team|Uttar Pradesh]]\n| year3 = 2015/16\u20132017/18\n| clubnumber3 = \n| club4 = [[Kings XI Punjab]]\n| year4 = 2019\n| club5 = Mumbai\n| year5 = 2019/20\n| clubnumber5 = \n| columns = 3\n| column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| column2 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 cricket|T20]]\n| matches1 = 17\n| runs1 = 1,463\n| bat avg1 = 66.50\n| 100s/50s1 = 4/4\n| top score1 = 301[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries1 = 78\n| wickets1 = 0\n| bowl avg1 = \u2013\n| fivefor1 = \u2013\n| tenfor1 = \u2013\n| best bowling1 = \u2013\n| catches/stumpings1 = 11/\u2013\n| matches2 = 13\n| runs2 = 257\n| bat avg2 = 36.71\n| 100s/50s2 = 1/0\n| top score2 = 100\n| deliveries2 = 6\n| wickets2 = 0\n| bowl avg2 = \u2013\n| fivefor2 = \u2013\n| tenfor2 = \u2013\n| best bowling2 = \u2013\n| catches/stumpings2 = 